Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and attach handlers to all six events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Created");
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Deactivated");
        window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Stopped");
        window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Resumed");
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Destroying");

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Key things to watch for in your logs:**

| Transition | You'll see |
|---|---|
| First launch | `Created` → `Activated` (no `Resumed`) |
| Notification shade / dialog | `Deactivated` only (not `Stopped`) |
| Full background then return | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Resumed` → `Activated` |
| Android back-button close | May go straight to `Destroying`, skipping `Stopped` |

**Pitfall:** `Resumed` never fires on the initial launch — only after a `Stopped` → foreground cycle. If you need logic on *every* foreground entry, use `Activated`.
